\begin_layout Section*
Abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Group A streptococci (GAS) and group C/G streptococci (GCS/GGS) cohabit
 the same ecological niche.
 We investigate exchange of genetic elements between GAS and GCS/GGS using
 their genomes.
 The study shows that the two groups exchange genetic segments across the
 entire genomes not just housekeeping genes.
 It shows that more genetic elements flowed overall from GAS to GCS/GGS
 than the other direction.
 We found no evidence that virulence genes were exchanged more than other
 regions of the genome.
 Three functional categories show higher recombination rates: biosynthesis
 in fatty acid and phospholipid metabolism, phosphoenolpyruvate:carbohydrate
 phosphotransferasesystem (PTS) in signal transduction, and tRNA aminoacylation
 in protein fate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
S.
 pyogenes
\emph default
 (SPY) is a pervasive human-specific pathogen which causes a wide variety
 of streptococcal diseases.
 The closely related species 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
 (SDE) has long been thought of as a veterinary pathogen, but recent evidence
 suggests that it can cause serious and life-threatening human diseases
 traditionally associated with SPY 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Brandt2009"

\end_inset

.
 Because these two species cohabit the same ecological niche, genetic exchanges
 between the two groups seem likely.
 In this study we explore patterns of recombination between these species,
 as well as rates of duplication, loss, and transfer.
 One question we are trying to address is whether these genetic exchanges
 from SPY to SDE could have played a role in the formation of pathogenicity
 of SDE.
 Previous studies were limited to housekeeping genes partly because of a
 lack of methods for studying bacterial recombination on the genome scale,
 and partly due to unavailability of relevant bacterial genomes.
 We have utilized the ClonalOrigin software 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Didelot2010"

\end_inset

 to study patterns of recombination between five Streptococcus genomes.
 ClonalOrigin takes a reference species tree and uses an MCMC framework
 to add recombinant edges to the tree, exploring a state space of possible
 ancestral recombination graphs (ARGs).
 Each recombinant edge represents transfer of genetic material from a donor
 genome to a recipient genome.
 We first used progressiveMauve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Darling2004,Darling2010"

\end_inset

 to align the genomes of the five species: 
\emph on
Streptococcus pyogenes
\emph default
 MGAS315 (SPY1), 
\emph on
S.
 pyogenes
\emph default
 MGAS10750 (SPY2), 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
 ATCC 12394 (SDE1), 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
 GGS_124 (SDE2), and 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
dysgalactiae
\emph default
 (SDD).
 This resulted in 415 alignment blocks with lengths of at least 500 base
 pairs.
 The reference species tree was inferred by ClonalFrame 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Didelot2007"

\end_inset

, and was in agreement with the one used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Suzuki2011"

\end_inset

.
 ClonalOrigin could then be applied to these alignment blocks and species
 tree.
 The results enable us to create a map of recombination rates across each
 genome (Figure 1).
 We observe high variation in recombination rates, including several loci
 which seem to be hotspots for bacterial recombination.
 A preliminary gene ontology (GO) analysis suggests that categories having
 to do with sugar phosphotransferase and fatty acid biosynthesis may be
 enriched for high levels of recombination.
 We are also able to look at the rates of genetic transfer between all branches
 of the species tree.
 Figure 2 shows the amount of gene flow to and from each species relative
 to the expectation under the prior.
 We find that there appears to be more gene flow from SPY1 and SPY2 to SDE1
 and SDE2 than in the other direction.
 We are also exploring gene duplication, loss, and horizontal gene transfer
 using a complementary approach.
 We used the clusters of gene families computed by OrthoMCL 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Li2003,Suzuki2011"

\end_inset

.
 These include the five species from ClonalOrigin analysis, and also the
 outgroup S.
 equi subsp.
 equi strain 4047.
 For each family cluster, the corresponding peptide sequences were aligned
 using the MUSCLE program 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Edgar2004a"

\end_inset

 and nucleotide alignments were constructed by mapping nucleotide sequences
 onto each peptide alignment.
 Gene trees were created for each nucleotide alignment using the RAxML program
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stamatakis2006a"

\end_inset

 and were rooted by minimizing duplications and losses.
 Each rooted gene tree was then reconciled using the Mowgli program 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doyon2011"

\end_inset

, which inferred the most parsimonious gene duplication, loss, and transfer
 events for each family.
 Figure 3 shows the inferred gene counts for each extant and ancestral species.
 Overall, we find that duplications make up only a small fraction of the
 events within the clade (9.6%), while horizontal transfers and losses are
 significantly more frequent (37.5% and 52.9%, respectively).
  We also find that duplications are most often species-specific.
  Many gene losses likely represent horizontal transfers that replace the
 native gene sequence.
 The relatively high number of transfers into SDE1 and SDE2 seems to support
 the findings from the ClonalOrigin analysis, although our investigation
 is ongoing.
