\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pathogenic bacteria infect many human diseases: e.g., food poisoning by 
\emph on
Eschericha Coli
\emph default
, strep throat by 
\emph on
Streptococcus pyrogenes
\emph default
, tuberculosis by 
\emph on
Mycobacterium tuberculosis
\emph default
, cholera by 
\emph on
Vibrio cholera
\emph default
, anthrax by 
\emph on
Bacillus anthracis
\emph default
, pneumonia by 
\emph on
Streptococcus pneumoniae
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Chlamydophila pneumoniae
\emph default
, and influenza by 
\emph on
Haemophilus influenzae
\emph default
, to name a few (a single CITE).
 Among them,
\emph on
 Streptococcus pyogenes
\emph default
 belongs to group A streptococci (GAS) that are a human-specific pathogen
 primarily infecting the throat and skin (CITE).
 This human pathogen has high prevalence throughout the world causing severe
 invasive streptococcal diseases: pharyngitis also called strep throat,
 impetigo, cellulitis, necrotizing fasciitis, toxic shock syndrome, acute
 rheumatic fever, and acute glomerulonephritis (CITE).
 Its closely related species, 
\emph on
Streptococcus dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
, belongs to group C or G streptococci (GCS or GGS), once generally regarded
 as veterinary pathogens (CITE).
 Researchers have been confirming that GCS/GGS can cause serious and life-threat
ening streptococcal diseases to human traditionally associated with GAS
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Brandt2009"

\end_inset

.
 Because 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
 cohabits with 
\emph on
S.
 pyogenes
\emph default
 at the same ecological niche of tissue sites, they may as well exhibit
 overlap in the disease profile 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Davies2007a"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, genetic interaction between the two species may have played
 roles in formation of pathogenicity of 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
.
 Understanding the genetic exchange could enhance our knowledge of their
 pathogenic effect on human health.
 Previously experimental research in gene exchange between the two pyogeneic
 species was limited to relatively smaller portion of the bacterial genome,
 mostly focusing on virulence genes
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kalia2004,Towers2004,Bessen2005"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Davies2007a"

\end_inset

 tackled a genome-wide profiling of virulence genes of the two species using
 microarrays.
 An earlier attempt at resolving the direction of gene flow between the
 two species seemed unfortunately premature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see"
key "Kalia2001"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, certain virulence genes appear to have originated from one to another,
 and vice versa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bessen2010"

\end_inset

.
 Lateral gene transfer in bacteria is so prevalent, and lack of gene exchange
 is considered unusual in bacterial evolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Didelot2010b"

\end_inset

.
 Biological mechanisms that induce lateral gene transfer include conjugation
 by plasmid, transduction by bacteriophages, and transformation of naked
 DNA uptake 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Thomas2005"

\end_inset

.
 Transferred DNAs through the machanisms replace their endogenous homologs,
 involving homologous recombination (CITE).
 Bacteria appear to benefit from recombination to acquire genetic material
 that is selectively advantageous 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vos2009"

\end_inset

.
 Although lateral gene transfer by homologous recombination has driven bacterial
 evolution, methodological development has hardly been able to deal with
 properly the important evolutionary force.
 Bacterial phylogenetic studies recognized early on that lateral gene transfer
 would complicate analyses of evolutionary relationships of the species
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Woese1987"

\end_inset

.
 Methods of infferring phylogenies in the presence of laternal gene transfer
 have been proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Bapteste2004,Simonson2005,Beiko2009"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, most of the methods use relatively small portion of bacterial genomes,
 which is an unfortunate situation.
 As sequencing costs plummet 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mardis2011"

\end_inset

, bacterial genomes sequencing produces genomes of high quality in many
 bacterial species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tettelin2009a"

\end_inset

.
 Given high prevalence of laternal gene transfer via homologous recombination
 in bacteria, values of complete bacterial genomes must not be understated
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fraser2002"

\end_inset

.
 Development of downstream analysis methods using bacterial genomes appears
 to lag behind that of high-throughput sequencing technology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Green2011"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Didelot2010"

\end_inset

 developed a powerful statistical method, and implemented it into a software
 called ClonalOrigin.
 The method uses a reference species tree inferred using bacterial genomes.
 The reference species tree serves as a back-bone where additional edges,
 hereafter I refer to as recombinant edges, are attached to the species
 tree branches.
 A recombinant edge connects two branches of the reference tree.
 The authors describe that a recombinant edge ``departs'' from an older
 time point at a species branch, and ``arrives'' at a more recent time point
 of another species branch.
 The arrival point corresponds to a recombination event in an ancestral
 recombination graph (ARG).
 As the reference tree traverses a genome alignment to meet a recombinant
 edge, its sister branch of the arrival point is erased and the recombinant
 edge replaces it.
 Consequently, gene trees change sequentially along a genome.
 This reminisces about gene conversion modeling by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wiuf1999"

\end_inset

, and the sequential Markov coalescent due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "McVean2005"

\end_inset

.
 Although recombinant edges between two species branches do not denote gene
 flow between two species in their original model, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Didelot2010"

\end_inset

 exploited their method to infer flow of genetic segment between 
\emph on
Bacillus cereus
\emph default
 species.
 Here we applied the method of ClonalOrigin to scrutinze intensity of gene
 flow between the two species of 
\emph on
S.
 dysgalactiae
\emph default
 spp.
 
\emph on
equisimilis
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
S.
 pyogenes
\emph default
.
 We hope that this study could be a step towards the understanding of interactio
n between the two closely related human pathogens.
 Specifically, we wish to answer to three questions.
 Firstly, did two species exchange genetic segments across the entire genome
 or parts of the genome? What proportion of the genome underwent higher
 recombination? Secondly, if the two pyogenic species exchanged genetic
 segments, was it overall unidirectional or bidirectional? Thirdly, what
 classes of genes were exchanged if they exchanged genetic material? 
\end_layout

